FTIR spectrum of the CQDs (Fig. 3
                        ) is displayed in the range of 400–4000 cm−1. The FTIR analysis was done after freeze-drying the CQDs solution. The bands at 3388, 2924, 1275 cm−1 related to the stretching vibration of O–H, C–H, and C–NH–C functional groups, receptivity. The peak in the 1461 cm−1 shows bonding vibration of N–H groups. The peak at 1091 cm−1 was assigned to the C–O stretching vibrations [36]. These functional groups cause good solubility in water and conjugation with other biomolecules. The surface of the CQDs is full of carboxyl and amine groups, and displays strong adsorption of the base of the aptamer oligonucleotides through π-π stacking interactions that lead to the effective quenching of fluorescence as shown in Fig. 3A. PCL exhibited its characteristic bands at 2940 cm−1 for asymmetric CH2 stretching, 2860 cm−1 for symmetric CH2 stretching, 1240 cm−1 for asymmetric C–O–C stretching and 1180 cm−1 for OC–O stretching. After modification of PCL NFs by CQDs, FTIR spectrum had significant differences in bands in comparison to PCL, suggesting molecular interaction between PCL and CQDs. Peak intensity at 1651 cm−1 is related to stretching vibration of –CONH– in NFs that shows significant formation of amide bond between PCL and CQDs [35,37]. After crosslinking and modification of NFs by aptamers the peaks and their intensity altered generally. Peak intensity at 1690 cm−1 is related to imine bonds after cross-linking the NFs by glutaraldehyde. Significant decreasing in the 3500 cm−1 bonds which is related to hydroxyl groups on the surface of NFs, showing the interaction between aldehyde groups of glutaraldehyde with hydroxyl groups and the bond at 1150 cm−1 is related to CO interactions resulted from crosslinking. The peaks at 1042 and 1362 cm−1 in the FTIR of modified NFs by aptamers were assigned to stretching mode of phosphates (PO2
                        −) and aromatic C–N groups of nucleotides of aptamers, respectively, that show aptamers were successfully immobilized on the surface of NFs. The biocompatibility of the modified NFs was evaluated by cytotoxicity experiments against fibroblast cells through the MTT assay. The cell viability test data was obtained after incubation of the cells with the PCL NFs, NF-CQDs, and NF-CQD-aptamers, as shown in Fig. 3B. The number of viable cells after incubation with the modified NFs were found to be slightly decreased in the presence of CQDs and aptamer and the viability of cell was found to be ∼94%, 92%, and 90%, respectively. It is well reported that this smart NF structure is nontoxic against living cells and could be biocompatible and safe for in vivo applications and use on skin wounds. The hemolysis test, which involved spectrophotometric measurement of hemoglobin release following exposure to NFs, was used to investigate the effect of NFs on erythrocytes. After the NFs enters the blood, it interacts with RBCs. To assess the impact of NFs on erythrocytes, a hemolysis test was performed by spectrophotometric measurement of hemoglobin released after exposure to NFs. The performance of the hemolysis assay was tested using PBS as the negative control and Triton-X-100 as the positive control (Fig. 3C). The hemolytic activity of NF showed caused ∼5% hemolysis.

Respectively, Fig. 6
                         and Fig. S6 show high and low magnification of fluorescence microscopic images of aptamer–NFs that became responsive, and the recovery of emissions of modified NFs at different excitation wavelengths occurred. Blue, green, and red color emission were recorded from the aptamer-NF membranes when it was excited at 405 nm, 488 nm, and 543 nm with a laser, respectively. There was low emission in aptamer-NFs in absence of S. aureus but after adding specific bacteria the fluorescence emission increased. The detection performance of the biosensors using the NF membranes fabricated following functionalization was compared with other methods for S. aureus detection (Table 1
                        ). The high performance of modified NFs has advantages for biosensing applications, including being easy and portable, not requiring time-consuming procedures, the possibility of naked eye monitoring, high sensitivity and selectivity, inherent stability, biocompatibility, and high production yield. Utilization of aptamers and CQDs make this smart biosensor cheaper compared to other developed using other biomolecules such as antibodies or bacteriophages and other quantum dots or dyes.
